INSIDE ARIZONA RESEARCH

As we cross the midpoint of the fall semester, momentum across University of Arizonas research and partnerships is unmistakable. Starting next month, you will see that progress as Inside Arizona Research transitions into Convergence Point, a monthly digest that goes deeper on innovation, collaboration, outcomes and opportunities at the U of A. Expect richer narratives, compelling research stories and partnership highlights, alongside the insightful content you have come to expect, such as federal updates. It all combines into one powerful read, curated to reflect how discovery really happens: over time, across disciplines and with impact.

Thanks for being with us see you at the Convergence Point.

Toms Daz de la Rubia
Senior Vice President for Research and Partnerships

ACHIEVEMENTS & ADVANCES

U of A named top public university in the Southwest

The University of Arizona ranks No. 1 in the Southwest and among the top 25 U.S. public universities in Times Higher Educations global rankings. See how the U of As research and industry impact earned this distinction.

Convergent team tackles deadly heat with innovative health tech

Backed by the Big Idea Challenge, the Heat and Health Resilience Innovation Consortium is developing wearable monitors, cooling kiosks and AI tools to protect Arizonas most vulnerable residents. See how this statewide effort could shape global heat health strategies.

Study finds potential link between chronic pain and rare immune condition

U of A researchers found 12% of high-impact chronic pain patients had eosinophilia, a rare immune response seen in less than 1% of the general population. Read how this finding could shape future chronic pain research.

Moons largest crater may reveal clues to its fiery past

New U of A research shows a giant impact unearthed radioactive material from deep inside the moon, providing rare insight into how it formed and evolved. Find out what scientists hope to uncover.

U of A tech aims to improve skin cancer diagnosis

Backed by a $2.7M NIH award, U of A researchers are developing synthetic wavelength imaging to help doctors assess tumor margins and monitor treatment. See how this noninvasive technology could fill a critical gap in skin cancer care.

SEEDING INNOVATIVE GROWTH

NSF 25-514: NSF Scholarships in Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics program (Tracks 2 and 3)

Internal Deadline: October 15, 5:00 PM

The S-STEM program seeks to increase the number of academically promising low-income students who graduate with an S-STEM eligible degree and contribute to the American innovation economy with their STEM knowledge. Recognizing that financial aid alone cannot increase retention and graduation in STEM, the program provides awards to institutions of higher education not only to fund scholarships, but also to adapt, implement and study evidence-based curricular and co-curricular activities that have been shown to be effective in supporting recruitment, retention, transfer, student success, academic/career pathways and graduation in STEM.

Solicitation // Limit: 2 // Tickets Available: 1 

APPLY

2025 New Directions fellowship program

Internal Deadline: October 15, 5:00 PM

One of the core aims of Mellon's Higher Learning program is to elevate the knowledge that informs fuller narratives of the human experience. Supporting the expansion and evolution of humanities disciplines through investing in the range and productivity of exceptional faculty is crucial to this objective. New Directions fellows undertake systematic training outside their fields of specialization to acquire the competencies required for advanced cross-disciplinary research research that goes beyond traditional boundaries and offers innovative and effective ways of bringing humanistic knowledge to bear on social challenges. 

With this objective in view, Higher Learning invites nominations of highly qualified scholars in the humanities or humanistic social sciences who received their doctorates between 2013 and 2019. This by-invitation competition will provide grants of up to $300,000 over three years. They anticipate allocating up to $4 million for this call; the final number of proposals selected will depend on the number and substance of the submissions.

Solicitation // Limit: 1 // Tickets Available: 1 

APPLY

2026 National Digital Newspaper program

Internal Deadline: October 15, 5:00 PM

The National Endowment for the Humanities Division of Preservation and Access is accepting applications for the National Digital Newspaper program. This program creates a national digital resource of historically significant newspapers published between 1960 and 1963 from all 50 states and six U.S. jurisdictions. The Library of Congress maintains this freely accessible, searchable online database.

APPLY

NSF's Eddie Bernice Johnson INCLUDES initiative

Application deadline: October 28, 2025 

The NSF's Eddie Bernice Johnson Inclusion across the Nation of Communities of Learners of Underrepresented Discoverers in Engineering and Science initiative is a national effort to foster inclusive change in STEM by broadening participation among underrepresented groups. It supports systemic, collaborative infrastructure-building through five project typeslaunch pilots, consortia, alliances, network connectors and conferencesthat contribute to a diverse, cross-sector national network. Proposals are submitted through the Directorate for STEM Education but managed by a multidisciplinary team, aligning with NSFs strategic goals for inclusive excellence and long-term competitiveness. Explore more about INCLUDES.

2025 Human Exploration Research Opportunities notice of funding opportunity

Application deadline: October 30, 2025 

NASAs Human Exploration Research Opportunities notice of funding opportunity invites applied research proposals supporting the Human Research Program, aimed at advancing human health and performance in space exploration. Research areas span five HRP elements: space radiation, human health countermeasures, exploration medical capability, human factors and behavioral performance and research operations and integration. Awards range from under $250K to $1.2M annually, with project durations from one to five years. Proposals follow a two-step submission process. Read more about HERO.

Studies assessing the clinical meaningfulness of insulin dose in type 1 diabetes

LOI Due: November 5, 2025

People with type 1 diabetes take lifelong insulin therapy to compensate for a partial or complete lack of endogenous insulin production. Intensive insulin therapy is absolutely required for glucose control, avoidance of diabetic ketoacidosis and reduction of the risk for long-term complications. It is generally thought that therapeutic approaches allowing insulin dose to be reduced without compromising glucose and ketone control will be beneficial for people with T1D. This request for applications is intended to solicit proposals investigating the effects of insulin dose and insulin dose reduction on acute and long-term T1D outcomes.  Find out more about the studies assessing the clinical meaningfulness of insulin dose in type 1 diabetes.

Studies addressing clinically relevant questions about ketones and the use of continuous ketone monitoring in type 1 diabetes

LOI Due: November 12, 2025

Circulating ketones are clinically relevant metabolites in type 1 diabetes. To date, most of our knowledge about ketones in T1D has come from point-of-care blood and urine ketone measurements, which provide only snapshots in time and lack the temporal resolution needed to fully understand ketone dynamics. Today, emerging continuous ketone monitors allow us to answer questions we never could before about the pathophysiology of T1D and its complications, diabetic ketoacidosis prevention and other topics. Breakthrough T1D invites letters of intent for studies addressing clinically relevant questions about ketones and the use of continuous ketone monitoring in T1D.  Find out more about the studies addressing clinically relevant questions about ketones and the use of continuous ketone monitoring in type 1 diabetes.

THE VIEW FROM WASHINGTON, D.C.

President Trump signs new executive order on AI and pediatric cancer *

On September 30, President Trump signed an executive order titled Unlocking Cures for Pediatric Cancer with Artificial Intelligence. It aims to incorporate artificial intelligence into various aspects of pediatric cancer research and expand on the Childhood Cancer Data Initiative, which was established in 2019 under the first Trump Administration.

It specifically highlights the potential for AI to bolster the CCDI to produce meaningful solutions to pediatric, adolescent and young adulthood cancer. The executive order empowers the Make American Healthy Again Commission to coordinate with the Secretary of Health and Human Services, Assistant to the President for Science and Technology and Special Advisor for AI and Crypto to develop methods to use AI for improved diagnoses, treatments, cures and prevention strategies focused on pediatric cancer.

It notes that this work should be done in alignment with the Administrations recently released AI Action Plan , and the initial focus of the initiative should be to identify how to accelerate the CCDI through AI by making data platforms and tools available as part of the CCDI Data Ecosystem. The order also directs the MAHA Commission to coordinate with the HHS Secretary, Office of Management and Budget, National Institutes of Health Director and APST to prioritize expanding pediatric cancer research by increasing investment from existing federal funds" for the CCDI and other federally funded pediatric cancer research initiatives. See here for Lewis-Burkes full analysis of the executive order.

Related to the ongoing dispute over government funding, Congress is still far apart on a deal to end the government shutdown. Click here for Lewis-Burkes most up to date guidance and information on federal agency implementation of the shutdown.

ON THE HORIZON

Finding your path to NEH Fellowships

Oct. 30, 2025 I 1:00 PM - 2:00 PM | Grand Challenges Research Building

Are you curious about National Endowment for the Humanities funding? Join Research Development Services for an engaging session on how to approach NEH opportunities, with a focus on the competitive NEH Fellowship program. Youll gain practical insights into what NEH supports, how to frame your proposal and how humanities research fits into todays grant landscape.

Well also introduce the 2026 NEH Fellowship Writing Group, a four-month program offering structured support and peer feedback. Open to faculty across disciplines and career stages, the group is designed to help sharpen ideas and strengthen proposals ahead of the April deadline.

Land Acknowledgment

We respectfully acknowledge the University of Arizona is on the land and territories of Indigenous peoples. Today, Arizona is home to 22 federally recognized tribes, with Tucson being home to the Oodham and the Yaqui. The university strives to build sustainable relationships with sovereign Native Nations and Indigenous communities through education offerings, partnerships, and community service.
